Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as a second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after Czechia, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated actively in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But Poland’s path to space had begun a long time earlier.
Before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts had made space flights, but this was not always understood.
I recall, for example, A. Sterfeld's lecture, which, on 6 December 1933, represented an idea to the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory from his innovative work "Introduction in Space".
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadowski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri Award and André Luis Hirsch in France for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadowski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Hadomsky became a prominent world promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the other side of the Moon had been named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway cutter equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea was not known, nor were the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket had to be used for the crash or for the braking of the trolley.
The only information on this is known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has begun to think about missiles.
The study was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mechisław Wolfke and Gustav Mokzitzki.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, a specialized press introduced the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket proposed by an engineer of Rogozinski, and next year the work of the “Levia-Kivolotsk Air Missile and Air Bomb” was launched.
Both projects were developed for the military use of missile engines.
Before the war itself, the Interim Scientific and Advisory Committee (Tymczasaw Komitet Doradczo-Naukouy) was responsible for all military missile projects, which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended because of the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work on space appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the Polish Society of Astronautycine (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautycone).
For the first time, social issues are referred to in the November 1954 issue of the magazine “Problems”, which contains four voluminous articles on astronauts.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotović proposed to organize a community that would be involved in space.
By that time, artificial satellite projects had been gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since early 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join the international Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and has already become an effective member of the Astronautics Society of Poland (PAA).
The following year, Kaziz Zarankevich, First President of the PAA (02-1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautics Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful RM Meteorological Missile, which was the first Polish rocket to carry out a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of reaching 1,800 metres, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
An improved RM-1A version was subsequently built and two-stage RM-2 missile tests were carried out in the Blades Desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to carry out real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have been over 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-velocity wind.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
The first RM-type missile was inherited by the Meteorological 1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed to be two-step, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteorological-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed which were different in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteorological-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 litres, the Meteorological 1B had a volume of 0.34 litres, and the Meteorological 1C had a volume of 0.62L.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteorological 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight testing began in October 1970.
The Meteorological 2 rocket, with a start weight of 380 kg, was capable of delivering a useful load of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Then version 2N and meteor-3 were built.
Reference should also be made to Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Space Research Committee) in 1960 and to the establishment of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
