Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning ' s stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires the closure of the case on the grounds that the conditions of Manning ' s detention were harsh.
The U.S. Private Army is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, had not availed himself of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he claimed he had to undergo while in a military prison.
During the pre-trial interrogation in Fort Mida, Maryland, the Military Prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that the records of the weekly visits to Manning by the prison authorities in nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
Cross-examined as part of the defence ' s appeal for the termination of the Manning case, on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was held the day after Manning had stated that he had intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 was accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
The WikiLeaks resource did not confirm that the source of the information was Manning.
During the hearing on Friday, the Fein Prosecutor, together with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been filled after the visits of the administration to Manning during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was in strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his responses.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he valued treatment by the prison administration as “precious” and general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized”.
The reports under consideration do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, although Manninga was directly asked about his conditions of detention, Feyn claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about these issues and that the authorities who visited him had discussed these issues with him and had stated that they would be dealt with but not recorded in writing.
"They wrote no "problems," but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the subject in a conversation," says Manning.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission dealing with suicide intentions, which he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that during that meeting he wanted to be removed from the “prevention of injury” regime and eased conditions of detention.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited regime of detention - below the level of supervision for the prevention of suicide - had been introduced to protect the prisoner and to protect others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them to stop the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living could improve, in my view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that one day he had lost consciousness because of the heat.
He explained that it is very difficult when you are not told how your destiny is handled and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has appealed to Camp Arifjan's base, to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I'd die in this cage."
While in Quantico, Manning said that he spent most of his time in a small cell, at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day, alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only his mattress, blankets, slippers, a few items of clothing and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because sleeping or even lying in the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep he was constantly struck by the light coming out of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face as he turned around in bed at night, he said he was woken up and forced to turn around.
The Manning lawyer filed a formal objection to the ill-treatment of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manninga was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about the statement he had made during his testimony on Thursday that, after one night he had been forced to sleep naked in his cell at Quantico, he had been forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners on an morning check.
