That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he was going through while in detention and significantly reduce the sentence if Manning was found guilty by the military court, which was due to commence his trial at the beginning of the following year.
The defence stated that it planned to offer Manning a confession for less serious crimes and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and it is expected that the prosecution will insist that conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
The charges against Manning include aiding the enemy, facilitating illegal publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defence and stealing State property or documents.
If convicted on all counts of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
