Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas can be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The usual, senseless disputes over who started the first time; many buildings were turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, the majority of whom were civilians, and six Israelis, were killed; for the first time in the course of the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of Israel ' s capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, although the Israelis and the Palestinians have been hopelessly tied in their age-old conflict, the Middle East has seen a change.
This can be said in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have surrounded many persistent realities in the insurgency, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that rocked the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their fight will become even more bloody than it was before.
There are, however, reasons for hoping to break this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the situation does not seem to give rise to optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, signed on 21 November, is being implemented, the clashes that took place this week have only strengthened the positions of the militia on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement that came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007 will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite their losses.
Despite the fact that some faction leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million residents blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements increases in the Arab world, Hamas has new, powerful and rich friends.
The reviving regional leader of Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and dynamic developing States in the Persian Gulf.
The solemn supporters of Hamas claim to have established an Islamist lunar around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by the Hezbollah paramilitary group, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad ' s power, and further to Jordan, where the king ' s allies threaten Hamas.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, Egypt, where the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened under President Mohammed Murcy.
Hosni Mubarak, who had ruled Egypt for 30 years and had been overthrowed in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay particular attention to Hamas support.
The Muslim brothers are, on the contrary, an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more inclined to populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced, even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the hard line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli iron dome missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of Hamas-launched missiles.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States remained faithful to its stand; many European countries had also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis have been killed since 2004 by rockets fired from Gaza, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombings, partly through the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River — a significant part of an unrecognized Palestinian State — and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu ' s position, whose party Likud - in preparation for the 22 January elections - has been merged with more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Liberman, is very comfortable.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they were given over to all authority in the West Bank, would they not begin firing missiles from there towards Israel, as they were gathered in the Gaza Strip?
It's better to hold them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempt to lift their heads.
A hard line might win; however, its calculation could be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be their domestic problems.
Israel ' s defence budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
Warfare with the regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who worked with Barak Obama to put a ceasefire on hold, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, to a lesser extent, take into account the long-term implications of its policies.
As democratic changes have taken place in the Arab countries, the denial of the right to self-determination of the Palestinians constitutes a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the occupied territories of Israel, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression was already undermining the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension of Arab population growth was only exacerbating those problems.
The bloody operations carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement must be paid for by the international community ' s growing discontent.
Both parties need an external impulse
There is only one solution that is consistently called upon by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israeli concessions of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will enable other countries to have a more effective impact on the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which had long overdue decided to stop arms transfers to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar had a more favourable position than ever in order to persuade Hamas to recognize the boundaries of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the sharing of the territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more for the establishment of a Palestinian State than the forthcoming vote in the United Nations, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama also has a role to play in placing Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
Upon his return to the White House, he continued to demonstrate his reluctance to engage in a solution to the problem.
It is a disastrously shortsighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Uniform Packing Act for cigarettes entered into force in Australia.
